      deepDive:
        "Your decisiveness is qualitatively different from impulsive types who decide fast because they don't deliberate. You decide fast because your experiential function has already pre-loaded the relevant data: 'We've been in this situation before. This is what worked. This is what didn't. Here's the move.' Your lead function then executes on that assessment with the organizational confidence that comes from knowing how to make the decision stick — assigning responsibilities, setting deadlines, establishing checkpoints. This combination of speed and thoroughness is rare and extremely valuable in managerial and administrative contexts. Where impulsive types decide and forget, you decide and follow through. Where cautious types deliberate until the window closes, you act while the option is still available. The specific risk: your decisiveness is built on precedent, which means it's most reliable in situations that resemble the past and least reliable in genuinely novel situations. When the environment has fundamentally changed and the old playbook no longer applies, your experiential function may confidently recommend exactly the wrong response. The skill to develop: recognizing the difference between 'this situation looks familiar' and 'this situation is familiar.' They're not always the same.",
